04862nam a22007095i 9780226196817DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226196817  a(DE-B1597)524282  a(OCoLC)993115899  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHV6593.E8515bS66 2017 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a364.1530943155090342231 aSpector, Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aViolent Sensations :bSex, Crime, and Utopia in Vienna and Berlin, 1860-1914 /cScott Spector. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b36 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: On the Border -- t1. Dark City, Bright Future: Utopian and Dystopian Urban Genres around 1900 -- t2. Identical Origins: (Homo)sexual Subjects and Violent Fantasy in the 1860s -- t3. Sensation and Sensibility: Experts, Scandals, Subjects -- t4. Utopian Bodies: The Sensual Woman and the Lust Murderer -- t5. Blood Lies: The Truth about Modern Ritual Murder Accusations and Defenses -- tConclusion: Utopia -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAround the turn of the twentieth century, Vienna and Berlin were centers of scientific knowledge, accompanied by a sense of triumphalism and confidence in progress. Yet they were also sites of fascination with urban decay, often focused on sexual and criminal deviants and the tales of violence surrounding them. Sensational media reports fed the prurient public’s hunger for stories from the criminal underworld: sadism, sexual murder, serial killings, accusations of Jewish ritual child murder—as well as male and female homosexuality. In Violent Sensations, Scott Spector explores how the protagonists of these stories—people at society’s margins—were given new identities defined by the groundbreaking sciences of psychiatry, sexology, and criminology, and how this expert knowledge was then transmitted to an eager public by journalists covering court cases and police investigations. The book analyzes these sexual and criminal subjects on three levels: first, the expertise of scientists, doctors, lawyers, and scholars; second, the sensationalism of newspaper scandal and pulp fiction; and, third, the subjective ways that the figures themselves came to understand who they were. Throughout, Spector answers important questions about how fantasies of extreme depravity and bestiality figure into the central European self-image of cities as centers of progressive civilization, as well as the ways in which the sciences of social control emerged alongside the burgeoning emancipation of women and homosexuals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBlood accusationzEurope, CentralxHistoryy19th century. 0aCivilization, Moderny19th century. 0aHomosexualityzEurope, CentralxHistoryy19th century. 0aLust murderzEurope, Centraly19th century. 0aMarginality, SocialzEurope, CentralxHistoryy19th century. 0aSex crimes in literature. 0aSex crimesxPress coveragezEurope, CentralxHistoryy19th century. 0aSex crimeszAustriazViennaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSex crimeszEurope, CentralxHistoryy19th century. 0aSex crimeszGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ablood libel.  acrime.  acriminology.  ahistory of sexuality.  ahomosexuality.  alustmord.  ametropolis.  asensation.  asexology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022619664040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226196817423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/do